<sn><md>#### Solodization or Dealkalization

- The process involves `removal of sodium ion` ($\text{Na}^+$) from the `exchange sites` with much dispersion of soil clays. 
- ++Dispersion occurs++ when the $\text{Na}^+$ ion becomes `hydrated` and much of dispersion can be eliminated if $\text{Ca}^{2+}$ and/or $\text{Mg}^{2+}$ are concentrated in water used to leach the alkali soils as they can replace sodium on the exchange complex.

The reaction can be represented as:

$$2\text{ NaX} + \text{CaSO}_4 \longrightarrow \text{Na}_2\text{SO}_4 + \text{CaX}$$

This may be the `final stage` in the transition and the resulting soil is known as **soloth**, which have light coloured surface horizon over a heavy dark brown B-horizon.</md></sn>